            <h2 id="how-compression-works">How PDF Compression Works</h2>
            <p>PDF files can be large for several reasons: high-resolution images embedded in the document, uncompressed fonts, metadata, and redundant data. A PDF compressor addresses each of these differently.</p>

            <p>There are two main types of PDF compression:</p>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--blue">
                <strong>Lossless compression</strong> reduces file size without any quality degradation. It works by removing redundant data, optimizing internal PDF structure, and compressing metadata. The visual output is identical to the original.
            </div>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--orange">
                <strong>Lossy compression</strong> achieves much greater size reduction by downsampling images — reducing their resolution. A 300 DPI print-quality image might be reduced to 96 DPI screen quality. Text remains sharp because it's vector-based, but embedded photos and graphics will show some quality loss.
            </div>

            <p>Most online PDF compressors use a combination of both. The best tools let you choose your compression level so you can prioritize either file size or quality depending on your use case.</p>

            <h3>What Actually Gets Compressed</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Embedded images</strong> — typically the biggest contributor to large PDF files</li>
                <li><strong>Fonts</strong> — subsetting fonts to include only the characters used in the document</li>
                <li><strong>Metadata</strong> — removing creation software info, edit history, and unused data</li>
                <li><strong>Duplicate content streams</strong> — eliminating repeated page elements</li>
                <li><strong>Color profiles</strong> — stripping embedded ICC color profiles not needed for screen viewing</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="when-to-compress">When Do You Need to Compress a PDF?</h2>
            <p>The most common scenarios where file size becomes a problem:</p>

            <div class="article-grid-2">
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">📧</div>
                    <strong>Email attachments</strong>
                    <p>Gmail limits attachments to 25MB. Outlook defaults to 20MB. A scanned document or presentation can easily exceed this.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">📤</div>
                    <strong>Web portals &amp; forms</strong>
                    <p>Government portals, job applications, and legal systems often cap uploads at 5–10MB.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">☁️</div>
                    <strong>Cloud storage</strong>
                    <p>Reducing file sizes stretches your Google Drive, Dropbox, or OneDrive storage further.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-card">
                    <div class="article-card-icon">📱</div>
                    <strong>Mobile sharing</strong>
                    <p>Large PDFs are slow to load and share on mobile. Compressed files open instantly.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2 id="what-to-look-for">What to Look for in a PDF Compressor</h2>
            <p>Not all PDF compressors are equal. Here are the criteria that matter:</p>

            <div class="article-checklist">
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Compression quality options</strong> — A good tool gives you control over the compression level, not just a one-size-fits-all approach.</div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Privacy &amp; security</strong> — Your files should be processed securely and deleted after. Look for clear data retention policies.</div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>No watermarks</strong> — Many free tools add visible watermarks. Choose a tool that doesn't degrade your document.</div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Output preview</strong> — Being able to see the compressed result before downloading builds trust.</div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>File size limit</strong> — Free tiers often cap at 5–25MB. Know your limit before uploading.</div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Batch processing</strong> — For professionals handling multiple documents, batch compression saves significant time.</div></div>
            </div>

