            <h2 id="quality-vs-size">Balancing Quality vs File Size</h2>
            <p>The right compression level depends entirely on how the document will be used:</p>

            <div class="article-grid-3">
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--green">
                    <div class="article-level-label">Low Compression</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">~20–35% smaller</div>
                    <p>Best for: Legal documents, contracts, medical records, any document that may be printed or archived. Quality is indistinguishable from the original.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--yellow">
                    <div class="article-level-label">Medium Compression</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">~40–60% smaller</div>
                    <p>Best for: Business reports, presentations, PDFs shared by email. Good balance of quality and file size for most professional use cases.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--red">
                    <div class="article-level-label">High Compression</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">~60–80% smaller</div>
                    <p>Best for: PDFs that only need to be read on screen, forms submitted to portals, or any document where storage space is the priority over visual quality.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2 id="tips">Pro Tips for Better PDF Compression</h2>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">1</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Remove unnecessary pages before compressing</strong>
                    <p>Use a PDF editor or split tool to remove blank pages, cover sheets, or appendices you don't need. Fewer pages means a smaller file even before compression.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">2</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Choose the right export settings at the source</strong>
                    <p>If you're creating a PDF from Word, PowerPoint, or another app — export at the appropriate DPI for the intended use. Exporting at 300 DPI for a document that will only be read on screen adds unnecessary file size.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">3</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Compress after merging, not before</strong>
                    <p>If you're combining multiple PDFs, merge them first then compress the combined document once. Compressing individual files and then merging can actually result in a larger final file.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">4</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Use batch compression for bulk documents</strong>
                    <p>If you regularly process 10–20 PDFs, manual one-at-a-time compression is a productivity killer. PdfToolStack's <a href="/batch">batch processing</a> lets you compress up to 20 files simultaneously with a single download.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">5</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Check the output file size before downloading</strong>
                    <p>A good compressor tells you the output file size before you commit to downloading. If the reduction isn't sufficient, try a higher compression level.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

