            <!-- FAQ -->
            <div class="article-faq">
                <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Does compressing a PDF reduce image quality?</summary>
                    <p>It depends on the compression level. Low and medium compression typically doesn't produce noticeable quality differences when viewing on screen. High compression reduces image resolution, which may be visible if you zoom in on photos or print the document. Text remains sharp at all compression levels because it's stored as vectors, not pixels.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Can I compress a PDF that already has a password?</summary>
                    <p>Most online PDF compressors require you to unlock a password-protected PDF before compressing it. Use a <a href="/unlock-pdf">PDF unlock tool</a> first, then compress the file.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Why is my PDF not getting smaller after compression?</summary>
                    <p>Some PDFs are already highly optimized — particularly those created from Office documents with no embedded images. If your PDF is mostly text with simple formatting, there may be little to compress. PDFs with high-resolution photos or scans show the most dramatic size reductions.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Is it safe to compress confidential documents online?</summary>
                    <p>It depends on the tool. PdfToolStack processes files over an encrypted HTTPS connection and automatically deletes all files within 1 hour. We never train AI models on your documents or share files with third parties. For highly sensitive documents, look for tools with explicit data deletion policies.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>What's the difference between compressing a PDF and converting it to a smaller format?</summary>
                    <p>Compressing a PDF keeps it as a PDF but reduces its internal data. Converting to another format (like JPG or PNG) changes the file type entirely and is usually not what you want for documents. Stick with PDF compression to maintain the document format, searchability, and text quality.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>How much can I reduce a PDF file size?</summary>
                    <p>Results vary significantly by document type. A 10MB PDF with many high-resolution photos can often be reduced to 2–3MB (70–80% reduction) at high compression. A 10MB PDF that's mostly formatted text with simple graphics might only reduce to 7–8MB. PDFs from scanned physical documents tend to see the largest reductions.</p>
                </details>
            </div>

